The SWHP is another type of water source heat pumps that also requires the presence of groundwater, but this system relies on other kinds of water sources, such as ponds, lakes, rivers, and seas [76]. Unlike GWHPs, SWHPs are available as both open and closed loop systems (see Fig. 3
                        )
                        [77]. Water is pushed from the water supply to the heat pump and then returned far from the extraction point in the open loop design (see Fig. 3a). A heat exchanger is utilized in the closed loop SWHP to allow heat transfer between the heat pump and the groundwater. As opposed to an open loop, the closed loop arrangement uses less pumping power, which results in cheaper operational costs. Coiled GHEs are frequently used in closed loop SWHPs, as seen in Fig. 3b. High-density polyethylene (HDPE) is mostly used as the pipe material for such heat exchangers. Given its flexibility and excellent thermal characteristics, HDPE is a good choice for these applications.
